The '''Foumban Shear Zone''', or '''Central Cameroon Shear Zone''' (CCSZ), is a [[fault zone]] in [[Cameroon]] that has been correlated with the [[Pernambuco fault]] in northeastern [[Brazil]], which splays from the [[Trans-Brazilian Lineament]].<ref name=Fairhead2007>{{cite journal |url = http://pubs.getech.com/publications/The%20Role%20of%20Gravity%20and%20Aeromagnetic%20Data%20in%20Mapping%20Mega%20Gondwana%20Crustal%20Lineaments%20the%20Argentina%20Brazil%20%20Algeria%20(ABA)%20Lineament.pdf |title = The Role of Gravity and Aeromagnetic Data in Mapping Mega Gondwana Crustal Lineaments: the Argentina - Brazil – Algeria (ABA) Lineament |author1 = J D Fairhead |author2 = Nasreddine Bournas |author3 = M Chaker Raddadi |journal = SEG |year = 2007 |accessdate = 2011-01-30 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711090717/http://pubs.getech.com/publications/The%20Role%20of%20Gravity%20and%20Aeromagnetic%20Data%20in%20Mapping%20Mega%20Gondwana%20Crustal%20Lineaments%20the%20Argentina%20Brazil%20%20Algeria%20%28ABA%29%20Lineament.pdf |archivedate = 2011-07-11 |df = }}</ref> It is part of the [[Central African Shear Zone]] (CASZ) and dates to at least 640 million years ago. The zone was rejuvenated several times, usually with a [[Fault (geology)|dextral]] movement, before and during the opening of the South Atlantic in the [[Cretaceous]] period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://horizon.documentation.ird.fr/exl-doc/AInv/1986-GJRAS-Adamawa.pdf |title=A teleseismic delay time study across the Central African Shear Zone in the Adamawa region of Cameroon, West Africa |author1=C. Dorbath |author2=L. Dorbath |author3=D. Fairhead |author4=G. W. Stuart |work=Geophys. J. R. astr. Soc. |year=1986 |pages=751–766 |accessdate=2011-01-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807114345/http://horizon.documentation.ird.fr/exl-doc/AInv/1986-GJRAS-Adamawa.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-07 |df= }}</ref>
The Foumban shear zone is a series of faults associated with major [[mylonite]] zones, a segment of the CASZ. The CASZ can be traced from the [[Sudan]] to the [[Adamawa plateau]], after which its path is obscured by volcanoes. Based on reconstruction of the configuration of South America before it separated from Africa, the zone can be identified with the Pernambuco fault.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://horizon.documentation.ird.fr/exl-doc/pleins_textes/pleins_textes_5/b_fdi_18-19/23236.pdf |title=CRUSTAL STRUCTURE OF THE ADAMAWA PLATEAU CAMEROON |author1=G. W. STUART |author2=J.D. FAIRHEAD |author3=L. DORBATH |author4=C. DORBATH |journal=Rev. Sci. et Tech. Sér Sci. Terre |year=1985 |accessdate=2011-01-31}}</ref> The shear zone underlies a chain of active volcanoes, called the [[Cameroon Volcanic Line]]. In August 1986 a magnitude 5 earthquake with epicenter near [[Lake Nyos]] indicated that the shear zone may be again reactivating.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FMRSzurkjkgC&pg=PA23&lpg=PA23 |journal=New Scientist |date=12 Feb 1987 |title=Quake may have triggered Nyos disaster |accessdate=2011-01-31}}</ref>{{vague|date=August 2015}}
