{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}
The '''Spartan Packet Radio Experiment''' ('''SPRE''') was an Amateur Radio communications experiment that flew on the [[Space Shuttle]] ''[[Space Shuttle Endeavour|Endeavour]]''{{'}}s [[STS-72]] mission as part of [[NASA]]'s Spartan/OAST-Flyer spacecraft in January 1996.<ref>http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/shuttle/missions/sts-72/mission-sts-72.html</ref> The experiment was intended to test the tracking of satellites via amateur packet radio ([[Automatic Packet Reporting System]]), and was designed and built by the [[Amateur Radio Club|Amateur Radio Association]] at the [[University of Maryland]] (W3EAX).<ref name="amsat.org">http://www.amsat.org/amsat/ftp/news/1995/ans343.txt</ref><ref>http://www.w0cra.org/news/960103cn.html</ref> Required [[GPS]] data for the experiment was provided by another portion of 
the Spartan payload.<ref name="amsat.org"/> The operating mode was [[Frequency modulation|FM]], [[AFSK]] 1200 [[baud]] packet radio, transmitted at 145.550&nbsp;MHz.<ref>http://www.hamradio-online.com/1995/nov-dec/spartan.html</ref>

