'''Waterwolf''', or '''Water-wolf''' is a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] word that comes from the [[Netherlands]], which refers to the tendency of [[Lake|lakes]] in low lying [[Peat|peaty]] land, sometimes previously worn-down by men digging peat for [[fuel]], to enlarge or expand by [[flooding]], thus [[Erosion|eroding]] the lake shores, and potentially causing harm to infrastructure or death.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.waterinitiativeforthefuture.org/blog/the-many-faces-of-the-waterwolf-the-low-countries-greatest-friend-and-foe|title=The many faces of the Waterwolf, the Low Countries’ greatest friend and foe.|website=Water Initiative for the Future (WatIF)|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> The term waterwolf is an example of “[[:nl:Waterwolf_(animalisering)|Animalization]]” , in which a non-living thing is given traits or characteristics of an animal (where a non-living thing given human traits or characteristics is [[personification]]). The traits of a wolf most commonly given to lakes include “something to be feared”, “quick and relentless”,” an enemy of man”.<ref name=":0" />
The Netherlands, meaning “low countries” is a nation where 18% of the countries’ land is below [[sea level]], and half of the land under one meter above sea level, and is prone to flooding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.bl.uk/european/2014/02/the-battle-of-the-floods.html|title=The Battle of the Floods - European studies blog|website=blogs.bl.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> Before modern flood control, severe [[Storm|storms]] could cause flooding that could wipe out whole villages in the area of the waterwolf.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1982/1209/120971.html|title=How Dutch shooed the 'waterwolf' from door|date=1982-12-09|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2018-05-09|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> Much of the land in the Netherlands is considered peat [[Bog|bogs]]. Peat is known to be an [[organic matter]] substance consisting of 10% carbon and 90% water and is usually found in colder [[Climate|climates]] where the [[plant growth]] and plant decay are slow. Peat is considered a [[carbon sequestration]], and when dried can be burned as a fuel. Historically peat was the primary source of fuel in the Netherlands, and farmers would mine the peat to burn or sell, thus contributing to the erosion of the [[landscape]].
The first great step to reclaiming land taken by the waterwolf was made with the creation of [[Windmills in the Netherlands|windmills]] that could pump water out of the surrounding area, allowing for the creation of [[polder]]s, or areas inhabited below sea level with an artificially managed [[water table]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allianz.com/en/about_us/open-knowledge/topics/environment/articles/100311-dutch-flood-protection-taming-the-water-wolf.html/|title=Dutch flood protection: Taming the water wolf - About us {{!}} Allianz|website=www.allianz.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> Modern flood control in the Netherlands consists of maintaining polders, [[Levee|levees]], and is highlighted by the world’s largest [[dam]] project: The [[Delta Works]].<ref name=":1" /> While modern flood control has conquered the waterwolf, new events such as rising sea levels from climate change could once again bring the waterwolf.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=18080442|title=California Turns to Holland for Flood Expertise|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref> See [[Flood control in the Netherlands|Flood Control in the Netherlands]] with the most notable "waterwolves" conquered being the [[Haarlem Lake]] and the [[Braakman]].[[File:Kaart Haarlemmermeer wapen 1641.gif|thumb|Detail of a map by Jacob Bartelz Veris drawn in 1641 of the Haarlem Lake, with a poem by [[Joost van den Vondel]] topped by a Dutch Lion fighting the Waterwolf as an allegory of the Dutch struggle against floods]]
==References== <references /> * For reference, see the Dutch version: [[:nl:Waterwolf (animalisering)]]. ("animalisering" = "[[personification]] as an animal".) * ''De Waterwolf getemd. Over geschiedenis en volksleven van Haarlemmermeer'', edited by TJ. W.R. de Haan, with contributions by W. Jappe Alberts, Tj. W. R. de Haan, Historical Committee Haarlemmermeer, Polder Board of the Haarlemmermeer, and the Haarlemmermer town archives, Kruseman's Uitgeversmaatschappij, The Hague, 1970, OCLC ocm37651338 {{-}}
